class Solution:
    def countGoodSubstrings(self, s: str) -> int:
        n = len(s)
        k = ""
        count = 0
        for i in range(0,n-2):
            mp = {}
            for j in range(i,i+3):
                if s[j] in mp:
                    mp[s[j]]+=1
                else:
                    mp[s[j]] = 1
            if len(mp)==3:
                count+=1
        return count










#Time Complexity
n = len(s) → O(1)
Outer loop runs n - 2 times → O(n)
Inner loop always runs 3 times → O(3) = O(1)
Dictionary insertion/lookup is O(1) on average.
len(mp) is O(1).

So,

O(n×3)=O(n)

Time Complexity: O(n)

Space Complexity

In each iteration:

mp = {}

The dictionary stores at most 3 characters, because the window size is 3.

So the maximum size of mp is:

{
'a':1,
'b':1,
'c':1
}

At most 3 keys.

Therefore,

Space Complexity: O(1)

Interview explanation

You can say:

Time Complexity: O(n) because the outer loop runs n-2 times, and the inner loop always runs a constant 3 iterations.
Space Complexity: O(1) because the hash map stores at most 3 characters regardless of the input size.

This is the expected complexity analysis for your solution.
